272
00:16:04,965 --> 00:16:07,432
narrator: to play most woodwind instruments,   

273
00:16:07,434 --> 00:16:10,635
the musician blows air through a reed made of cane.  

274
00:16:10,637 --> 00:16:12,971
the reed vibrates to create sound,        

275
00:16:12,973 --> 00:16:15,639
just like the vocal cords in our throat.         

276
00:16:15,641 --> 00:16:18,910
a bassoon reed is comprised of two thin blades of cane   

277
00:16:18,912 --> 00:16:23,914
rather than one, so it's called a double reed. 

278
00:16:23,916 --> 00:16:28,185
[ bassoon playing "in the hall of the mountain king" ]    

279
00:16:28,187 --> 00:16:31,689
a bassoon reed has twin blades at the top       

280
00:16:31,691 --> 00:16:35,125
that vibrate to produce sound and a tube at the bottom    

281
00:16:35,127 --> 00:16:38,462
that fits onto the bassoon's lead pipe.    

282
00:16:38,464 --> 00:16:41,131
the reed maker begins with a stalk of cane      

283
00:16:41,133 --> 00:16:44,335
that's almost an inch in diameter.      

284
00:16:44,337 --> 00:16:46,537
with a single strike of a cylindrical,       

285
00:16:46,539 --> 00:16:47,738
x-shaped blade,        

286
00:16:47,740 --> 00:16:51,342
he splits it into four equal strips,    

287
00:16:51,344 --> 00:16:54,278
then uses a guillotine to cut each strip to a length 

288
00:16:54,280 --> 00:16:56,647
of 4 3/4 inches.        

289
00:16:58,951 --> 00:17:00,684
after soaking a strip in water 

290
00:17:00,686 --> 00:17:03,554
for about 8 hours to soften the fibers,     

291
00:17:03,556 --> 00:17:06,457
he laterally slices off about half the cane.      

292
00:17:11,364 --> 00:17:14,766
then, he places it in a precision gouger     

293
00:17:14,768 --> 00:17:17,835
and thins it to approximately 0.05 inches,          

294
00:17:17,837 --> 00:17:19,871
give or take a fraction of an inch.          

295
00:17:24,778 --> 00:17:27,978
he verifies the thickness   
with a precision-measuring tool,

296
00:17:27,980 --> 00:17:29,781
called a dial indicator.    

297
00:17:34,187 --> 00:17:38,655
he clamps the cane in a reed-shaped template   

298
00:17:38,657 --> 00:17:41,859
and trims away the excess.   

299
00:17:46,532 --> 00:17:49,367
this gives the cane a distinct contour.      

300
00:17:51,671 --> 00:17:54,338
he removes the outer layer of rigid bark         

301
00:17:54,340 --> 00:17:55,806
and thins out the middle,   

302
00:17:55,808 --> 00:17:59,343
which will become the dual blades of the reed.  

303
00:17:59,345 --> 00:18:02,413
next, he cuts a pattern that will enable the reed   

304
00:18:02,415 --> 00:18:05,416
to vibrate at the frequencies required to produce      

305
00:18:05,418 --> 00:18:08,886
the bassoon's full range of 44 notes.    

306
00:18:08,888 --> 00:18:11,021
then, he scores both ends of the cane     

307
00:18:11,023 --> 00:18:12,557
to make them flexible enough  

308
00:18:12,559 --> 00:18:14,725
to be bent into a half circle. 

309
00:18:17,163 --> 00:18:19,697
he folds the cane in half and ties it      

310
00:18:19,699 --> 00:18:23,634
with a piece of brass wire.  

311
00:18:23,636 --> 00:18:25,636
the fold will form the double blades       

312
00:18:25,638 --> 00:18:27,838
at the top of the reed.    

313
00:18:27,840 --> 00:18:29,039
the opposite ends,       

314
00:18:29,041 --> 00:18:31,041
once bent into mating half circles,         

315
00:18:31,043 --> 00:18:33,211
will form the tube at the bottom.         

316
00:18:35,715 --> 00:18:39,583
keeping the cane wet, he heats a cylindrical-forming mandrel 

317
00:18:39,585 --> 00:18:42,086
over the flame of an oil-burning lamp.    

318
00:18:45,858 --> 00:18:48,960
then, he wraps the tube end tightly with twine.    

319
00:18:52,865 --> 00:18:55,199
the heat softens the cane's fibers,       

320
00:18:55,201 --> 00:18:58,202
molding them under pressure from the tightly wound twine  

321
00:18:58,204 --> 00:19:00,938
to the shape of the mandrel.  

322
00:19:00,940 --> 00:19:03,674
this forms the two adjoining half circles     

323
00:19:03,676 --> 00:19:06,544
into a perfectly round tube.  

324
00:19:06,546 --> 00:19:07,811
after a few seconds,      

325
00:19:07,813 --> 00:19:09,880
he removes the forming mandrel 

326
00:19:09,882 --> 00:19:12,816
and unwraps the twine.     

327
00:19:12,818 --> 00:19:15,686
he inserts a holding mandrel of the same diameter      

328
00:19:15,688 --> 00:19:18,623
and wraps it with a rubber band.

329
00:19:18,625 --> 00:19:22,360
he puts the reed aside to dry for about a week.    

330
00:19:22,362 --> 00:19:25,963
this sets the shape permanently.

331
00:19:25,965 --> 00:19:28,765
when he unwraps and unfolds the reed,     

332
00:19:28,767 --> 00:19:31,835
he sands the edges of the two adjoining half circles     

333
00:19:31,837 --> 00:19:34,772
so that they meet perfectly.  

334
00:19:34,774 --> 00:19:37,241
then, he refolds the reed,   

335
00:19:37,243 --> 00:19:38,842
securing it with three wires  

336
00:19:38,844 --> 00:19:43,247
spaced at specific intervals. 

337
00:19:43,249 --> 00:19:44,715
the distance between the wires,

338
00:19:44,717 --> 00:19:47,117
in concert with the curved shape of the cane,       

339
00:19:47,119 --> 00:19:49,587
finalizes the contour of the reed,          

340
00:19:49,589 --> 00:19:53,390
which determines how it vibrates.        

341
00:19:53,392 --> 00:19:55,793
one the wires are correctly positioned,     

342
00:19:55,795 --> 00:19:57,594
he wraps the tube end of the reed          

343
00:19:57,596 --> 00:20:00,464
with strong synthetic string. 

344
00:20:00,466 --> 00:20:02,132
this will contain the tube dimensions      

345
00:20:02,134 --> 00:20:05,402
when the reed is resoaked.   

346
00:20:05,404 --> 00:20:07,405
he coats the string with glue 

347
00:20:07,407 --> 00:20:10,007
to further strengthen the tube.

348
00:20:10,009 --> 00:20:11,676
once the glue dries,      

349
00:20:11,678 --> 00:20:13,343
he reams the inside of the tube

350
00:20:13,345 --> 00:20:16,113
to fit perfectly into the bassoon's lead pipe.    

351
00:20:20,819 --> 00:20:23,754
he places a ruler against the first wire     

352
00:20:23,756 --> 00:20:24,955
and makes a mark of just    

353
00:20:24,957 --> 00:20:28,960
over an inch out toward the folded tip.     

354
00:20:28,962 --> 00:20:31,562
then, he clips off the folded tip.        

355
00:20:31,564 --> 00:20:33,831
the reed now has double blades 

356
00:20:33,833 --> 00:20:36,767
that vibrate when a musician blows air through them.    

357
00:20:36,769 --> 00:20:38,936
[ bassoon playing ]      

358
00:20:43,042 --> 00:20:46,443
because cane is a plant, not a synthetic material,   

359
00:20:46,445 --> 00:20:50,314
there are slight natural variations from reed to reed. 

360
00:20:50,316 --> 00:20:54,986
so bassoonists make the last minor adjustments themselves  

361
00:20:54,988 --> 00:20:57,654
with profilers and other tools 

362
00:20:57,656 --> 00:21:00,691
until their reed vibrates beautifully.     

